definitions.definition: ( auxiliary verb , defective ) To know how to.
examples: She can speak English, French, and German.

definitions.definition: ( auxiliary verb , defective ) To be able to.
examples: Can you remember your fifth birthday?
I can feel the baby moving inside me.

definitions.definition: ( modal auxiliary verb , defective , informal ) May ; to be permitted or enabled to.
examples: You can go outside and play when you're finished with your homework.

definitions.definition: ( modal auxiliary verb , defective ) To have the potential to; to be possible for (someone or something) to.
examples: Teenagers can really try their parents' patience.

definitions.definition: ( modal auxiliary verb , defective , informal ) Used to form requests, typically polite .
examples: Can you please come over here?
Can we try that scene again?

definitions.definition: ( India , nonstandard , proscribed ) To be ( followed by a word like able , possible , allowed ) . third-person singular simple present indicative of can
( Manglish , Singlish , auxiliary or intransitive ) To be able to or know how to (do something); an accompanying verb is not required if it is already inferable from context.

( Manglish , Singlish , intransitive ) To be fine or acceptable ; to be possible ; (with liao or already ) to be enough . Often used in conjunction with a variety of clause-final particles, e.g., lah , meh or one , to express different attitudes towards the subject matter.

examples: They canned air to sell as a novelty to tourists.

definitions.definition: To preserve by heating and sealing in a jar or can.
examples: They spent August canning fruit and vegetables.

definitions.definition: To discard , scrap or terminate (an idea, project, etc.).
examples: He canned the whole project because he thought it would fail.

definitions.definition: To fire or dismiss an employee .
examples: The boss canned him for speaking out.

definitions.definition: To cover (the fuel element in a nuclear reactor) with a protective cover.

main_definition: ( transitive ) To seal in a can.
